{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15871"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15871"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.03,0,0.93]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62992"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8562"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48443"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20554"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62992"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA hydrocele is a collection of serous fluid between the parietal and visceral layers of the tunica vaginalis. It characteristically presents as a painless swelling in the scrotum, which has slowly been increasing in size (Image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic of a hydrocele?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appears dark on transillumination","Contains blood-stained fluid","Persists indefinitely in congenital cases","Requires surgical correction in all cases","Transilluminates due to clear fluid content"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHydroceles are fluid collections around the testis that can be either congenital or acquired. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransillumination\u003C/strong\u003E is a key diagnostic feature due to the clear serous fluid content. The fluid is not \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood-stained\u003C/strong\u003E unless there is trauma or other pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile some hydroceles are \u003Cstrong\u003Econgenital\u003C/strong\u003E, these often resolve spontaneously within the first year of life as the processus vaginalis closes. It is incorrect that they \u003Cstrong\u003Erequire surgical correction in all cases\u003C/strong\u003E - intervention is only needed for persistent or symptomatic cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDue to the clear fluid content, hydroceles will \u003Cstrong\u003Eappear bright\u003C/strong\u003E rather than dark on transillumination, making this a reliable diagnostic test to differentiate from solid masses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A hydrocele is a fluid collection between the layers of the tunica vaginalis of the testis","Congenital hydroceles result from patent processus vaginalis and typically resolve spontaneously","Hydroceles transilluminate due to clear serous fluid content","Secondary hydroceles can occur due to infection, trauma, or tumours"],"references":["Huzaifa M, Moreno MA. Hydrocele. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559125/","Dagur G, Gandhi J, Suh Y, Weissbart S, Sheynkin YR, Smith NL, Joshi G, Khan SA. Classifying Hydroceles of the Pelvis and Groin: An Overview of Etiology, Secondary Complications, Evaluation, and Management. Curr Urol. 2017 Apr;10(1):1-14. doi: 10.1159/000447145. Epub 2017 Mar 30. PMID: 28559772; PMCID: PMC5436019.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48443"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15871"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21197"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21197"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Zn7t2uZIhZm5UVZQjW7hhJZO8BFUFq.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Zn7t2uZIhZm5UVZQjW7hhJZO8BFUFq.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":493,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48443"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T14:33:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T18:52:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8562"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62992"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"at